constructor is one special block of any class 
constructor name should be same as class name
it should not have any return type.
we can not use static keyword also before constructor
when we are creating the object by using the new keyword, that time only constructor will be executed.
it is used to intialize all the non static variable of the class.

<--types of contructor-->
    we have two types of constructor.
        1.non parameterized constructor
        2.parameterized constructor


int the  Q2_class2.java programe there is no user definded constructor.
so it will execute default constructor.


<--non parameterized constructor-->


syntax:
    [accessmodifier] [modifierr] c lassname()
    {

    }

any constructor that does not have formal argument is called non parameterized constructor.


<--parameterized constructor-->
    constructor that having formal arguments is called parameterized contructor

syntax:
    [access modifier] [modifier] classname(formal arfument)
    {

    }

when we are creating object by using new kewword that time  only we have to pass the original arguments.

for each object we can assign different value by using this constructor.


<------------THIS----------------->
1.this is a keyword it is used to defind the current object
2.when we have local variable and instance variable same name that time for accessing the instance variable we can use this keyword.
3.this keyword we can not use inside static context.
4.this keyword is also called as reference variable.


<--------Constructor Chaining--------------->
when we are calling one constructor from another constructor is called constructor chaining.

we can do constructor chaining in same class as well as from different class.

in the same class if we want to do constructor chainging we need this() statement.

<-----------this() statement------------->
this() calling statement is used to perform constructor chaining.

this() statement should be the first statement in the constructor.

when we are calling another constructor by using this() 
if we are passing any arguments that should match with another constructor signature.

<----------constructor chaning in different class----------->
this is the process of calling super class constructor inside child class constructor.

<------------super() statement----------->
super() is used to perform constructor chaining in two  different classes.

it should be first statement inside the constructor.

if user is not giving super() , compiler will add that.

note: for ddoing constructor chaining in different 


now parent class constructor will load the

then it will retrun back to child class constructor and it will load all the nonstatic members inside the object in the heap area

here we can see we aree creating the object of child but it is loading the loading the properties of both parent and child.


<-----reference variable------->
this variable stores the address of object.

we can create multiple referance variable and we can store one referance vaiable into another variable.
 
by using this we can acess all the properties of the object.

package reference_variable;

example: 
class Qspider
{
    String loc="arumpakkam";
}


package reference_variable;

public class Jspider {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Qspider j1=new Qspider();
        Qspider j2=new Qspider();
        System.out.println("j1 address:"+j1);
        System.out.println("j2 address:"+j2);

        Qspider j3=j2;
        Qspider j4=j3;
        Qspider j5=j4;

        System.out.println("j3 address: "+j3);
        System.out.println("j3 address: "+j4);
        System.out.println("j3 address: "+j5);
        

    }
}

in thiis example ob1 and ob2 address will be different 
but ob2,ob3,ob4,ob5,address will be same.
